"""
MKT Original Commentary — Numbers 16–18
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-numbers-16-18.py

Key decisions:
- Ch 16: Korah rebellion — Korah is a Kohathite (carries the ark!) who seeks the priesthood;
  the rebellion has two strands: Korah's priestly claim + Dathan/Abiram's political grievance;
  Aaron's plague-stopping intercession (v47-48) is one of the most striking priestly acts in the Torah
- Ch 17: Aaron's rod — the budding/blooming/almond-bearing overnight is the divine authentication
  of the Aaronic priesthood; the staff kept before the ark = enduring sign (Heb 9:4)
- Ch 18: YHWH is Aaron's inheritance (v20) — the most concentrated statement of priestly
  calling in the Torah; tithe structure assigns Levites as living support for the sanctuary
- "YHWH" throughout per project convention
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NUMBERS = {
  "16": {
    "1": "<p><strong>Vayiqach Qorach</strong>: 'Now Korah took [men].' The verb <em>laqach</em> (take) without a direct object is grammatically anomalous — the text never states clearly what Korah took. Ancient readers noticed this; the LXX attempts to smooth it. The force may be: 'Korah took himself [and his followers]' — he took initiative, he seized the moment. Korah is a Kohathite (son of Izhar son of Kohath son of Levi) — the sub-clan that carries the most holy objects of the tabernacle, including the ark. He already occupies the most prestigious Levitical role; he wants more: the priesthood itself.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The coalition against Moses has two components: (1) Korah with his Levitical supporters (those seeking the priesthood); (2) Dathan and Abiram, Reubenites (who have a political grievance — Reuben is Jacob's firstborn and has been displaced). 250 leaders of the congregation (<em>qetziney ha'edah</em>) join them — men of renown (<em>anshey shem</em>). The rebellion is not a mob action but a coordinated challenge by the most prominent members of the community. This makes the judgment that follows especially severe.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>rav lachem ki kol ha'edah kulam qedoshim</strong>: 'You have gone too far! The whole congregation is holy, every one of them.' This is the theological claim of the rebellion: if YHWH's spirit rests on all Israel (a point Moses himself affirms in 11:29), what justifies the distinction between Levite and priest? The argument has a surface plausibility. The answer Numbers 16 gives is not that the claim is wrong (Exod 19:6 does call Israel a kingdom of priests) but that it is deployed in the wrong direction: the congregation's holiness does not eliminate YHWH's prerogative to appoint specific mediators.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>vayipol al panav</strong>: 'he fell on his face.' Moses's response to the challenge is not counter-argument but prostration — he brings the case immediately to YHWH. The same response appears at the golden calf (Exod 32:11-12) and at the spies' report (Num 14:5). Moses's pattern under pressure is intercession, not self-defense. This itself is the answer to Korah's charge: a man who responds to opposition by lying face-down before God is not an autocrat claiming privileges for himself.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>boqer veyoda YHWH et asher lo</strong>: 'In the morning YHWH will show who is his.' The word <em>yoda</em> (will show/make known) is the <em>Hiphil</em> of <em>yadah</em> (know) — YHWH will make known through the ordeal what he already knows. Moses proposes the censer-test: let each claimant bring incense before YHWH and YHWH will show whom he has chosen. This is judicial self-restraint — Moses does not assert his own authority but defers to divine demonstration.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The censer test: each man takes a <em>machtah</em> (censer/fire pan) — the same instrument Nadab and Abihu used when they offered strange fire (Lev 10:1) and the same instrument that the 250 authorized officiants of the tabernacle ceremony use. The invitation to bring incense is simultaneously an invitation to judgment: the correct use of the censer, by the correctly authorized person, is worship; the incorrect use brings death. Moses essentially says: bring your best case before YHWH and let him decide.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>rav lachem beney Levi</strong>: 'You have gone too far, sons of Levi!' Moses turns Korah's own charge back on him: it is the rebels who have gone too far (<em>rav lachem</em>), not Moses and Aaron. The formal chiasm between v3 (Korah: 'You have gone too far, all the congregation is holy') and v7b (Moses: 'You have gone too far, sons of Levi') is a deliberate literary reversal. Moses exposes that the rebellion is not about the congregation's holiness but about Korah's ambition.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Moses addresses Korah and his fellow Levites directly. The appeal to 'listen now, sons of Levi' (<em>shim'u na beney Levi</em>) uses the particle <em>na</em> (please/now) — a mark of respectful entreaty rather than command. Moses does not shout; he reasons with the rebels before the divine judgment falls. This deliberate appeal-before-judgment is the procedure Paul identifies as the prophetic calling: 'We implore you on behalf of Christ, be reconciled to God' (2 Cor 5:20).</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>hame'at mikem ki hivdil Elohey Yisrael etchem me'adat Yisrael</strong>: 'Is it too small a thing for you that the God of Israel has separated you from the congregation of Israel?' The rhetorical question exposes the ingratitude at the core of the rebellion. YHWH has already elevated the Levites above the congregation for sanctuary service — a privilege Korah treats as insufficient. <em>Hivdil</em> (to separate, <em>Hiphil</em> of <em>badal</em>) is the verb of consecration and distinction: YHWH's own creative act of separation (Gen 1:4, 6) is applied to the Levites' privileged calling.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>utevaqqeshu gam kehunah</strong>: 'And yet you seek the priesthood too!' The accusation is direct: Korah seeks both the Levitical privilege (which he already has) and the priestly privilege (which is Aaronic). <em>Tvaqqeshu</em> (you seek/demand) is covetous reaching beyond one's calling. Moses's point is that YHWH has already given the Levites more than the congregation receives — the demand for more is not championing equality but coveting a different status altogether.</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>lachen atah vekhol adatcha hano'adim al YHWH</strong>: 'Therefore it is you and all your company who have gathered against YHWH.' The rebellion is reframed in its ultimate dimension: this is not a grievance against Moses and Aaron but against YHWH himself. Moses asks the rhetorical question that devastates Korah's argument: 'What is Aaron that you grumble against him?' Aaron holds his office by divine appointment, not personal ambition — to grumble against Aaron is to grumble against the God who appointed him.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Moses summons Dathan and Abiram, who refuse to appear: 'We will not come up.' The refusal itself is an act of rebellion — a summons from Moses is a summons from YHWH's appointed leader. The Reubenites' grievance (v13-14) is different from Korah's: not priestly ambition but political resentment — Moses has 'brought them out of a land flowing with milk and honey' (ironically calling Egypt the promised land) and 'has not brought them into a land flowing with milk and honey.'</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>ha'at ki he'elitanu me'eretz zavat chalav udevash lahamitenu bamidbar</strong>: 'Is it too small a thing that you have brought us up out of a land flowing with milk and honey to kill us in the wilderness?' The bitter irony: Egypt is called the land flowing with milk and honey — the precise designation of Canaan. The inversion is deliberate mockery of Moses's language, exposing how deeply the failure to enter Canaan (Num 13-14) has poisoned the mood of the community. Dathan and Abiram have adopted the rebellious perspective of the spy-report: the promised land is unattainable and the exodus was a mistake.</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>af lo el eretz zavat chalav udevash heviatanu</strong>: 'You have not brought us into a land flowing with milk and honey.' The charge is factually correct at this moment in the narrative — but it ignores the reason: the congregation's own refusal (Num 14). Dathan and Abiram accuse Moses of failure while suppressing the community's role in that failure. The phrase 'will you put out the eyes of these men?' (<em>haeynot ha'anashim hahem tenaqqer</em>) is obscure but seems to mean: 'Do you think you can blind us to the truth?' — an accusation of deliberate deception.</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>wayichar leMoshe me'od</strong>: 'Then Moses was very angry.' The only clear expression of Moses's personal anger in this episode — prompted by Dathan and Abiram's contemptuous refusal and false charges. His prayer to YHWH 'do not accept their offering' (<em>al tepen el minchatam</em>) invokes the same language Cain feared (Gen 4:5): the withdrawal of divine acceptance. Moses then makes his own record: 'I have not taken one donkey from them, nor have I harmed any of them' — a selfless leader defending his integrity.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Moses instructs Korah: the test will happen tomorrow at the tabernacle — Korah and his 250 men vs. Aaron, all bringing censers. The symmetry of the test is notable: Korah claims that all the congregation are equally holy; the ordeal will demonstrate whether all 251 men (Korah + 250 + Aaron) are equally holy, or whether Aaron's election is unique. The test is fair by its own logic: if Korah is right, his censer will be accepted; if Aaron is right, the 250 will die.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Each of the 251 men brings his censer — 250 for the challengers, one for Aaron. The number 250 is specific and will be recalled at v36-40 when the censers become a memorial plating. The gathering of this many leaders with incense censers at the tabernacle entrance is the most public possible confrontation — the entire congregation is watching (v19). The drama is at maximum before the verdict falls.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The 250 men stand at the entrance of the tent of meeting with their censers burning — the same physical position Aaron and his sons occupy during authorized priestly service. From the outside, the scene looks like a liturgical ceremony; from the inside, it is a challenge to the divine prerogative. YHWH's glory appears to the whole congregation precisely at this moment (v19), giving the judgment maximum visibility.</p>",
    "19": "<p><strong>vayiqahel aleihem Qorach</strong>: 'Korah gathered the whole congregation against them.' Korah has successfully rallied the entire community to his side — the same congregation that will need to be kept alive through the plague that follows. YHWH's glory (<em>kevod YHWH</em>) appearing 'to the whole congregation' is the dramatic pivot: before anyone dies, YHWH visually manifests. This is the last moment the congregation might repent.</p>",
    "20": "<p>YHWH commands Moses and Aaron to 'separate yourselves from this congregation so that I may consume them in an instant' (<em>ke'raga</em> = in a moment, in the blink of an eye). The immediacy of the divine threat is absolute — not a conditional warning but an impending execution. The fact that YHWH warns Moses and Aaron first, before acting, reflects the pattern of Num 14: YHWH allows time for intercession even when judgment is imminent.</p>",
    "21": "<p><strong>hibadelu mitoch ha'edah hazot va'achaleh otam keraga</strong>: 'Separate yourselves from this congregation so that I may consume them in an instant.' The verb <em>badal</em> (separate) appears again — YHWH had separated the Levites for service (v9); now he separates Moses and Aaron from the community before destroying it. The irony is sharp: Korah challenged the separations YHWH made; YHWH now makes a sharper separation — between the condemned and the saved.</p>",
    "22": "<p><strong>El Elohey harukhot lekhol basar</strong>: 'O God, the God of the spirits of all flesh.' This invocation — unique in the Torah — addresses YHWH as the source of the animating spirit in every living person. Moses and Aaron's intercession is grounded in the divine responsibility for all life: 'Shall one man sin, and will you be angry with the whole congregation?' The rhetorical question makes the case for the congregation's corporate innocence — not all of them conspired with Korah. YHWH accepts the logic and focuses the judgment.</p>",
    "23": "<p>YHWH's response to the intercession is precise rather than total: instead of consuming the whole congregation, he tells Moses to have the community separate from the specific tents of Korah, Dathan, and Abiram. The surgical narrowing of the judgment from 'whole congregation' to 'specific households' is the direct result of Moses and Aaron's intercession. Intercession changes the scope of the judgment.</p>",
    "24": "<p><strong>Korah Datan va'Aviram</strong>: The three named leaders are the specific targets of the earth's opening. The congregation must move away from their dwelling-tents. The divine instruction to separate creates a spatial boundary that simultaneously protects the innocent and marks the guilty for judgment. The act of moving away from their tents is itself a public declaration of whose side one is on.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Moses goes personally to Dathan and Abiram's tents, accompanied by the elders of Israel. The elders who follow Moses (despite the general grumbling) are the remnant who retain their loyalty. Moses goes to where the stubborn rebels are rather than waiting for them to come to the tabernacle — a last pastoral attempt to reach men who refused his summons (v12).</p>",
    "26": "<p><strong>suru na me'al ohaley ha'anashim harashah'im ha'eleh</strong>: 'Move away from the tents of these wicked men.' Moses publicly names Dathan and Abiram as <em>resha'im</em> (wicked ones) before the assembly — the first direct condemnation in this episode. 'Touch nothing of theirs, lest you be swept away in all their sins' — the contagion of sin is treated as physical: proximity to the condemned creates risk of being caught in their judgment. The congregation's obedience here is the same separating-from-the-condemned pattern that the NT applies to the church's handling of unrepentant sin (1 Cor 5:11).</p>",
    "27": "<p>The congregation separates; Dathan and Abiram emerge from their tents and stand at the entrance with their wives, sons, and small children — their whole households. The families' presence at the moment of judgment is both terrible and theologically significant: the rebellion's consequence falls on the household, not just the individuals. Ancient corporate identity means the household is implicated in the leader's choices. This is why the text will later note that Korah's children did not die (Num 26:11) — YHWH makes a specific exception within the household solidarity principle.</p>",
    "28": "<p><strong>bezo't tede'un ki YHWH shelachani</strong>: 'By this you shall know that YHWH has sent me.' Moses stakes his prophetic credibility on the outcome of the judgment: if these men die a natural death, YHWH has not sent Moses; if the ground does something unprecedented, YHWH has spoken through his prophet. This prophetic self-testing is remarkable — Moses does not pray for the miracle to happen; he simply declares that if YHWH acts, his own mission is confirmed. The 'sign-condition' is the most concentrated expression of prophetic authentication in Numbers.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The conditional: if they die naturally (<em>kemet kol ha'adam</em> = the common death of all mankind) or receive a normal visitation (<em>fequdat kol ha'adam</em>), then YHWH has not sent Moses. The stakes are absolute. Moses is not hedging — he is making a public, falsifiable claim about divine authorization. The 'natural death' option being explicitly excluded means the miraculous judgment that follows is unambiguous as divine action.</p>",
    "30": "<p><strong>im beriah yivra YHWH</strong>: 'But if YHWH creates something entirely new (<em>beriah</em>).' The word <em>beriah</em> (new creation) comes from the root <em>bara'</em> (create), used of God's creation in Gen 1:1. A ground-swallowing judgment would be an act of creation — as unprecedented as the original creation. The phrase anticipates Isa 43:19 ('I am about to do a new thing') and the NT's language of the new creation in Christ. Moses calls for a miracle using the vocabulary of original creation.</p>",
    "31": "<p><strong>vatibqa ha'adamah asher tachteihem</strong>: 'the ground under them split apart.' The immediacy is total — Moses finishes speaking and the earth opens. The narrative compression is deliberate: Moses's word and YHWH's act are virtually simultaneous, confirming that Moses spoke as YHWH's prophet. The splitting ground is the most visceral possible judgment — the earth itself becomes YHWH's instrument of execution.</p>",
    "32": "<p><strong>vatiftach ha'aretz et piha vatival otam</strong>: 'The earth opened its mouth and swallowed them up.' The anthropomorphic image — the earth with a mouth — depicts judgment as total, final, and irreversible. Not killed, not struck by plague, but swallowed whole: they disappear from the surface of the created world. 'Along with their households, all the people belonging to Korah, and all their possessions' — the comprehensive catalog of loss emphasizes the totality of the destruction.</p>",
    "33": "<p><strong>vayerdu hem vekhol asher lahem chayim she'olah</strong>: 'They went down alive into Sheol.' The phrase <em>chayim</em> (alive) is the opposite of the normal death trajectory — people go to Sheol after dying, not while still living. This is the most extreme form of the 'cut off' covenant judgment: not just death but annihilation, disappearance from both the living and the dead — entered the realm of the dead without passing through normal death. 'The earth closed over them, and they perished from the midst of the assembly.'</p>",
    "34": "<p>The surrounding Israelites flee at the sound of the condemned men's cries — 'lest the earth swallow us also!' The fear is both understandable and a warning to future generations: proximity to YHWH's judgment is dangerous. The fleeing congregation enacts the separation YHWH commanded (v24) through sheer terror. Their flight creates the visual image of the condemned standing alone as the earth opens under them.</p>",
    "35": "<p><strong>ve'esh yatse'ah me'et YHWH vatochal et hashamosh</strong>: 'Fire came out from YHWH and consumed the 250 men who were offering incense.' The fire from YHWH executing the 250 censers-bearers echoes the fire that consumed Nadab and Abihu (Lev 10:2 — the same formula, almost verbatim). The parallel is intentional: both episodes involve unauthorized incense-offering at the tabernacle; both result in divine fire. The connection establishes the pattern: YHWH's fire is the judgment for those who approach the sanctuary without authorization.</p>",
    "36": "<p>A new divine speech (v36-40) addresses the disposition of the censers. The 250 censers belong to the sanctuary — they were used in service before YHWH (even in unauthorized service) and are therefore holy. They cannot simply be discarded; they must be repurposed in a way that memorializes the judgment.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Eleazar (not Aaron — Aaron is kept away from corpse-impurity, Lev 21:11-12) is to take the censers from among the burning men and scatter the coals. The coals themselves are to be scattered away — they were the unauthorized fire, and the fire of YHWH has rendered them dangerous. The censers, however, have become holy through contact with YHWH's judgment-fire and must be treated accordingly.</p>",
    "38": "<p><strong>et machtot hachat'aim ha'eleh benafashotam</strong>: 'the censers of these men who sinned at the cost of their own lives.' The phrase <em>benafashotam</em> (with/at the cost of their lives) captures the self-destructive nature of their sin: they used their censers as weapons against their own lives. The censers are to be hammered into plating (<em>riqui'ay pechim</em>) for the altar — bronze from the condemned men's censers becomes the facing of the altar of burnt offering. The judgment is permanently inscribed in the altar's surface.</p>",
    "39": "<p>Eleazar carries out the command: the 250 bronze censers are hammered into altar plating. The same altar at which Korah's men stood with their unauthorized incense now bears the memorial of their judgment on its surface. Every subsequent authorized incense-offering at the altar is performed against the backdrop of the censer-plating reminder: unauthorized approach to YHWH's altar is lethal.</p>",
    "40": "<p><strong>zikaron libeney Yisrael lema'an asher lo yiqrav ish zar</strong>: 'a reminder to the Israelites that no unauthorized person — not of Aaron's line — should come near to offer incense before YHWH.' The word <em>zikaron</em> (memorial/reminder) is the same term used for the memorial stones at the Jordan (Josh 4:7) and the Passover memorial (Exod 12:14). The censer-plating is not decorative but didactic: a permanent visual warning inscribed on the most public object in the sanctuary. The phrase 'as YHWH directed him through Moses' closes the unit with the divine-authority frame.</p>",
    "41": "<p>The most astonishing verse in the chapter: the day after the earth-swallowing and the fire, 'the whole congregation of Israel grumbled against Moses and Aaron, saying: You have killed the people of YHWH.' The rebels who were destroyed are now called 'the people of YHWH' — the congregation inverts the divine verdict, treating the judged as victims and Moses and Aaron as murderers. This re-grumbling demonstrates the hard-heartedness that required the full generation to die in the wilderness (Num 14:29-35). Judgment does not automatically produce repentance.</p>",
    "42": "<p>As the congregation assembles against Moses and Aaron, the cloud covers the tent of meeting and YHWH's glory appears — the same theophany as in v19. YHWH's visible presence appears precisely when the congregation threatens Moses and Aaron, constituting a divine protection. Moses and Aaron turn toward the tent — the proper posture for receiving divine communication — as the glory is about to speak.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Moses and Aaron go to the front of the tent of meeting — between the approaching congregation and the divine glory, exactly the mediatorial position their calling requires. The same spatial arrangement that existed throughout the Korah episode (Moses and Aaron between YHWH and the people) is reproduced. They are the buffer zone between divine holiness and human rebellion.</p>",
    "44": "<p>YHWH speaks again with the same command as v21: 'Get away from this congregation so that I may consume them in an instant.' The repetition of the threat (same words, same immediacy) marks the escalation: the first judgment fell on the specifically wicked; this judgment threatens the entire congregation, which has compounded the sin by accusing Moses and Aaron of murder. The re-grumbling is treated as a new and greater rebellion.</p>",
    "45": "<p>Moses and Aaron fall facedown again — the third time in the chapter (v4, v22, v45) Moses prostrates himself under pressure. The threefold prostration marks Moses as the supreme intercessor in Numbers: every time YHWH threatens destruction, Moses's first response is to fall before YHWH. The plague has already begun (<em>hachel hanegef</em> = 'the plague has begun') — YHWH acts while Moses and Aaron are still prostrate.</p>",
    "46": "<p><strong>Moshe el Aharon qach et hamachtah</strong>: Moses instructs Aaron to take his censer, take coals from the altar, add incense, and run into the middle of the congregation to make atonement (<em>kapper</em>). This is the most concentrated atonement act in Numbers: the high priest runs with burning incense into the midst of a plague-struck crowd. The action uses the same censer that Korah's men used illegitimately — but Aaron is the authorized priest, using authorized fire, in an act of authorized intercession.</p>",
    "47": "<p><strong>vayarots Aharon el toch haqqahal</strong>: 'Aaron ran into the middle of the congregation.' The verb <em>ruts</em> (run) signals urgency — Aaron did not walk ceremonially but ran. This running high priest, incense burning, moves toward the dying in order to stand between them and the plague. The physical action embodies the theological function of priesthood: moving toward death in order to stop it, interposing oneself as the atoning mediator between YHWH's judgment and the people's lives.</p>",
    "48": "<p><strong>vayaamod beyn hamaytim uveyn hachayim vate'atsar hamaggefah</strong>: 'He stood between the dead and the living, and the plague was stopped.' The spatial description of Aaron — literally between the corpses and the living survivors — is the most vivid image of priestly mediation in the entire Torah. The plague stops at the point where the authorized atonement-smoke rises. The Levitical high priest physically occupying the boundary between death and life is the enacted image of what Christ does as the mediator: standing between humanity's death-sentence and YHWH's life.</p>",
    "49": "<p>The death toll: 14,700 — in addition to those who died in the Korah incident itself. The precision of the number (not 'thousands' but 14,700) marks this as a historical record. The plague's speed is implied by v47-48: it had 'already begun' and was stopped by Aaron's running intercession. The gap between 'already begun' and Aaron arriving suggests the 14,700 died in a very short time — YHWH's judgment is both swift and stoppable by authorized intercession.</p>",
    "50": "<p>The chapter closes with Aaron returning to Moses at the entrance of the tent of meeting — the plague had been stopped. The closing scene reunites the two brothers at the sanctuary threshold after Aaron's solo run into the dying crowd. The literary frame of the chapter (Moses and Aaron at the tabernacle entrance, v18, v43, v50) holds the entire rebellion-and-plague narrative within the tent-of-meeting context: all of it happens within YHWH's visible presence.</p>"
  },
  "17": {
    "1": "<p>A new divine speech introduces the rod-test — YHWH's definitive authentication of the Aaronic priesthood following the Korah rebellion. The timing is significant: the rod-test comes immediately after the plague of 16:41-50, while the people are still living with the memory of the earth-swallowing and fire and 14,700 dead. The rod-test will provide a permanent visual sign rather than a repeated verbal command.</p>",
    "2": "<p>YHWH instructs Moses to collect twelve staffs (<em>mattot</em>) from all the leaders of Israel — one per ancestral house (<em>bet av</em>), twelve representing the twelve tribes. The <em>matteh</em> (staff/rod) is both the symbol of tribal leadership and a measuring/counting implement. The choice of the staff as the test object is significant: it is the dead wood of authority, capable of producing new growth only if YHWH acts.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>uchtavta shem ish al matteihu</strong>: 'Write each man's name on his staff.' The names inscribed on the staffs make the test individually attributable and prevent later disputes about which staff belonged to whom. Aaron's name is specifically written on Levi's staff — the priestly claim is personal and tribal. When the staff buds, Aaron's name is on it: the authentication is both individual and institutional.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The staffs are placed 'before the covenant document' (<em>lifney ha'edut</em>) — in the most holy place, before the ark. The ark contains the covenant tablets; placing the staffs before the covenant document aligns the authentication procedure with the covenant's own authority. The twelve staffs before YHWH's covenant is the overnight divine jury: YHWH deliberates through the night and returns his verdict in the morning in the form of living growth.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>hayah ha'ish asher avchar bo mattehu yifrah</strong>: 'The man I choose — his staff will sprout.' The test's logic is elegant: a dead wooden staff cannot sprout unless YHWH acts. The sprouting is not metaphorical but botanical — the text specifies flowers, almonds, and new growth. YHWH's choice is not communicated through vision or voice but through botany: the order of creation responds to the Creator's word in a way that cannot be faked. The test also frames the issue as divine election (<em>asher vacharthi</em> = whom I have chosen) rather than human appointment.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Moses collects the twelve staffs; the leaders give their staffs willingly. The entire leadership structure of Israel participates in the test: every tribal leader submits his staff to overnight divine judgment. This is the ultimate democratic test — not twelve competing claims adjudicated by Moses's word, but twelve dead sticks laid before YHWH simultaneously.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>vayannach Moshe et hamaттот lifney YHWH be'ohel ha'edut</strong>: 'Moses placed the staffs before YHWH in the tent of the covenant.' The act of placement is the full extent of human agency in the test — Moses puts the staffs in the right place and steps back. What happens next is entirely YHWH's action. This is the model of authentic ministry: bring people and objects to the right place before YHWH, and let YHWH's own act be the authenticating sign.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>vayhi mimacharat vayavo Moshe el ohel ha'edut vehineh parach matteh Aharon lebeit Levi</strong>: 'The next day Moses went into the tent of the covenant, and there was Aaron's staff — it had budded, produced blossoms, and borne ripe almonds.' The triple botanical progression — <em>parach</em> (budded/sprouted), <em>vayatsets</em> (put forth flowers), <em>vayyigmal</em> (bore ripe fruit) — compresses the full growth cycle of an almond tree (weeks to months) into a single overnight. The almond (<em>shaqed</em>) has a secondary significance: <em>shaqed</em> comes from <em>shaqad</em> (to watch/be alert) — the almond is the 'watching tree,' the first to bloom in spring. YHWH uses the 'watching tree' to watch over his choice.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Moses brings all twelve staffs out before the whole congregation. Every Israelite can see the result: eleven dead sticks and Aaron's living, flowering, fruiting staff. The visual contrast is the verdict. The congregation's response ('they looked, and each man took his staff') is muted — there is no recorded grumbling or challenge. The botanical miracle is unanswerable.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>hashev et matteh Aharon lifney ha'edut lemishmerет le'ot livney meri</strong>: 'Put Aaron's staff back before the covenant document, to be kept as a sign against the rebels.' The command to preserve the staff permanently establishes it as an ongoing sign (<em>ot</em>) and warning (<em>lemishtemirat</em> = as a preserved thing). The budding staff joins the jar of manna and the covenant tablets in the covenant chest — three objects preserved before YHWH as testimony to specific acts of grace and judgment in the wilderness. Hebrews 9:4 lists all three items inside the ark.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Moses's obedience is noted with the standard compliance formula. The brevity of this verse after the dramatic overnight miracle creates a narrative decompression: YHWH spoke, Moses obeyed, the sign is in place. No further divine elaboration is needed — the budding staff is self-explanatory as divine authentication of Aaronic election.</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>hinnenu govim hafnu kulanu avadnu</strong>: 'We are dying, we are perishing, we are all lost.' The Israelites' response to the authentication miracles of chapters 16-17 is terror rather than confidence. The three synonymous expressions of destruction (<em>gava</em>, <em>avad</em>, <em>tam</em> = died, perished, finished) pile up in increasing despair. The very demonstrations of YHWH's holiness that authenticate the priestly system have also revealed the danger of YHWH's presence to the unprepared. The question the people pose at the end of the verse ('anyone who comes near the tabernacle shall die — are we all going to die?') is genuine theological crisis.</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>kol haqorev haqorev el mishkan YHWH yamut</strong>: 'Anyone who comes near the tabernacle of YHWH shall die — are we all going to die?' This despairing question is the theological climax of the Korah-to-staff sequence. The people have now seen: unauthorized approach to the sanctuary kills. Their question anticipates the NT's great high priest theology: if YHWH's holiness is genuinely lethal to the sinful, how can any sinner approach? The answer Numbers 18 provides is the priestly mediation system; the answer Hebrews provides is Christ, the permanent high priest who is 'holy, innocent, unstained, separated from sinners, and exalted above the heavens' (Heb 7:26), who opens access rather than closing it.</p>"
  },
  "18": {
    "1": "<p><strong>vatomer YHWH el Aharon</strong>: YHWH addresses Aaron directly — the only time in Numbers a divine speech is addressed to Aaron alone rather than through Moses. The content is the theological resolution of the question at 17:13: who bears the burden of the sanctuary's holiness so the people don't die? Answer: 'You and your sons and your ancestral house with you shall bear the guilt of the sanctuary.' <em>Tisa'u et avon hammiqdash</em> (you shall bear the iniquity of the sanctuary) — the priests absorb the covenant-liability that would otherwise destroy the people. This is the priesthood's protective function: they take on guilt so others don't have to.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Levites are brought alongside Aaron as assistants (<em>yillavu aleicha</em> — 'shall join themselves to you,' from the root <em>lava</em> which is also the etymology of Levi's name in Gen 29:34). The Levitical attachment to Aaron is etymologically embedded in the tribe's name: the Levites exist to be joined to the priesthood in service.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>veshameru mishmartecha umishmerет kol ha'ohel</strong>: 'They shall fulfill their duties to you and to the whole tent.' The Levites have general tent-of-meeting duties; the priests have specific altar and inner-sanctuary duties. The boundary is reinforced: 'they shall not come near the vessels of the sanctuary or the altar, lest both they and you die.' The life-or-death stakes of the division of labor are restated — not to oppress the Levites but to protect them from what would kill them.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The Levites join Aaron and keep the charge of the entire tent of meeting — all external service. The phrase 'no outsider (<em>zar</em>) shall come near you' reinforces the boundary established in 16:40 (the censer-plating memorial): no one outside the ordained succession may do the priestly work. <em>Zar</em> (stranger/unauthorized person) is the technical term for those excluded from priestly service, regardless of their tribal status.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>ushmartem et mishmeret haqqodesh ve'et mishmeret hamizbeach velo yihyeh od qetsef al beney Yisrael</strong>: 'You shall be responsible for the sanctuary and the altar, so that wrath does not fall on the Israelites again.' The word <em>qetsef</em> (wrath) is what produced the 14,700 deaths (16:46). The priests' faithful execution of their mediatorial duties is the structural protection against repeat divine wrath. Aaron's guardianship of the altar is not a privilege; it is the load-bearing wall between YHWH's holiness and the people's survival.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>va'ani hineh laqachti et acheychem haLevi'im mitoch beney Yisrael</strong>: 'Behold, I myself have taken your kinsmen the Levites from among the Israelites.' The emphatic <em>ani hineh</em> (I myself, behold me) makes YHWH the active subject of the Levites' appointment — they were not recruited by Aaron or Moses but taken by YHWH. They are described as 'a gift given to YHWH, to perform the service of the tent of meeting' — the Levites are simultaneously YHWH's gift to Aaron and Aaron's gift to YHWH in service.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>ve'attah ve'vanecha ittecha tishmerou et kehunatchem</strong>: 'You and your sons shall attend to your priestly duties for everything at the altar and within the veil.' The phrase <em>velechal asher mibbeit laparochet</em> (everything within the veil) defines the priests' exclusive inner-sanctuary access. Then the remarkable elevation: 'I give your priesthood as a gift of service.' The priesthood itself is described as a <em>mattanah</em> (gift) — not an earned status or a right but something YHWH gives. 'Any outsider who comes near shall be put to death.'</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>vayedabber YHWH el Aharon</strong>: A second direct address to Aaron (v8-20) establishes the priestly portions. 'I give you charge of my contributions — all the holy gifts of the Israelites — I give them to you and your sons as your portion and as a perpetual due.' The word <em>mashach</em> in this context means 'anointed due/portion' — the same root as <em>mashiach</em> (anointed one). The priestly provision is embedded in the anointing-theology: what Aaron's anointing grants is sustained by the system of holy gifts.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The most holy portion (<em>qodesh haqqodashim</em>) — what is not burned: grain offerings, sin offerings, and guilt offerings. These belong to Aaron and his sons 'as a most holy portion.' 'Every male among you shall eat it' — access restricted to males of the priestly line, eaten in the most holy place. The gradations of holiness in the priestly portions mirror the holiness-gradations of the sanctuary itself: the most holy offerings eaten in the most holy place.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>beqodesh haqodashim to'kelennu</strong>: 'In the most holy place you shall eat it.' The eating of most-holy portions inside the sanctuary is itself a priestly act — not just payment for service but participation in the holiness of the offerings. The priest eats within the sacred space, absorbing the food that has been consecrated to YHWH. This is the OT background for the eucharistic principle of NT theology: eating within the sacred space, consuming what has been offered to YHWH.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The wave offerings and the heave offerings that are not most-holy — these may be eaten by Aaron, his sons, and 'every clean one in your household.' The loosening of access (from 'males only in the holy place' for the most holy to 'every clean person in the household') reflects the graduated holiness of the portions. The provision extends to the priestly family — daughters, slaves, and any person bought into the household who is ritually clean.</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>kol chelev yitzhar vechal chelev tirosh vedagan reishitam</strong>: 'All the best of the oil, the wine, and the grain — the firstfruits they give to YHWH, I give to you.' The principle is firstfruits: the first and best of every harvest goes to YHWH, and YHWH gives it to the priest. The priest's portion is not a second-tier left-over but the firstfruits themselves — the best the land produces flows to YHWH and from YHWH to his ministers. Paul applies this principle to ministerial support in 1 Cor 9:13-14.</p>",
    "13": "<p>All the first ripe produce (<em>bikkurim</em>) of the land shall belong to the priests. The <em>bikkurim</em> (firstfruits) are the most theologically charged category of offerings — they represent YHWH's ownership of the land and the farmer's acknowledgment that the harvest comes from YHWH. The priest receives the firstfruits as YHWH's representative, holding the symbolic first-produce of every harvest.</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>kol cherem beYisrael lecha yihyeh</strong>: 'Everything in Israel that is devoted to destruction shall be yours.' The <em>cherem</em> (devoted thing/ban) is the category of objects given wholly to YHWH, irrevocably removed from ordinary use. The priest receives what has been dedicated to YHWH without reservation — the absolute consecrations, the things given with no expectation of return. The priestly portion reaches even to the irreversible gifts.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Every firstborn (<em>bechor</em>) of all flesh — human or animal — that is presented to YHWH shall be the priest's. The firstborn-redemption principle runs from Exod 13 through Num 18: the first male to open the womb belongs to YHWH, and YHWH gives it to the priest (or its redemption price). The logic: YHWH owns all first-birth, having been the one to pass over the firstborn of Israel (Exod 12) and consecrate all firstborn to himself.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Human firstborns are redeemed at five shekels from a month old. The specific age (one month) corresponds to the threshold at which the infant is counted in the Levitical census (Num 3:15) — old enough to be recognized as a viable life. The redemption price is fixed and public — no negotiation, no wealth-gradient. Every firstborn son costs the same five shekels to redeem from his YHWH-dedication.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The firstborn of clean animals (cow, sheep, goat) are not redeemed — they are sacrificed, their blood sprinkled, their fat burned, and their meat goes to the priest (like the breast of the wave offering and the right thigh). The firstborn of clean animals belong entirely to YHWH and to YHWH's ministers; no redemption option exists for them. The priest's portion includes both the redemption payments from human firstborns and the actual meat from animal firstborns.</p>",
    "18": "<p><strong>uvsaram lecha yihyeh</strong>: 'Their meat shall be yours.' The priestly meat-portion from firstborn animals is compared to the wave-offering breast and right thigh — the portions already established in Lev 7:31-34 as the priest's share. The comparison roots the new firstborn-meat provision in an established precedent: the priest has always received designated portions; the firstborn meat is another instance of the same principle.</p>",
    "19": "<p><strong>kol terumot haqqodashim... berit melach olam hi lifney YHWH lecha ulezar'aca ittach</strong>: 'All the contributions of the holy gifts... it is a covenant of salt forever before YHWH for you and for your offspring with you.' The phrase <em>berit melach</em> (covenant of salt) appears only here and in 2 Chr 13:5. Salt was used to preserve food — a covenant of salt is a perpetually preserving covenant, an irrevocable and incorruptible agreement. The priestly provision is not temporary but a permanent covenant with the Aaronic house.</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>va'ani hinneh chelqecha va'nachalatecha betoch beney Yisrael</strong>: 'I am your portion and your inheritance among the Israelites.' This is the most concentrated and theologically profound statement in chapter 18. YHWH himself — not land, not money, not livestock — is Aaron's <em>chelq</em> (portion) and <em>nachalah</em (inheritance). The priest has no land because he has YHWH. This verse is the foundation of the entire priestly theology of vocation: the minister's sufficiency is the God he serves, not any material holding. Moses applies the same principle to the Levites in Deut 10:9; the psalms apply it to any believer (Ps 16:5; 73:26). The NT applies it to Paul: 'I have learned in whatever situation I am to be content... I can do all things through him who strengthens me' (Phil 4:11-13).</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Levites' provision: all tithes in Israel are given to the Levites as their inheritance 'in return for their service, the service they perform at the tent of meeting.' The tithe-system supports the Levites the way the priestly portions support the priests. The logic is parallel: YHWH owns all the produce of the land (as its creator and Israel's overlord), and YHWH gives his portion to those who serve him — to the priests as most-holy portions and firstfruits, and to the Levites as the general tithe.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The separation principle is reinforced: ordinary Israelites must not approach the tent of meeting 'lest they bear sin and die.' The Levitical service protects the congregation by absorbing the sin-risk of sanctuary proximity — they stand between the people and the lethal holiness. This is the answer to 17:13 ('are we all going to die?'): no, because the Levites and priests are the designated absorbers of the sin-risk that the sanctuary generates.</p>",
    "23": "<p><strong>halevy hu ya'avod et avodat ohel mo'ed vehem yis'u avonam</strong>: 'Only the Levites shall serve at the tent of meeting, and they shall bear responsibility for any iniquity connected with it.' The Levites 'bear' (<em>nasa</em>) the iniquity — the same verb used for priestly guilt-bearing throughout Leviticus. The Levites are not just workers; they are mediatorial sin-absorbers whose service keeps the entire system from exploding into judgment on the congregation. Their service has an atoning dimension.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The rationale for the Levitical tithe: 'the tithe of the Israelites, which they present as a contribution to YHWH, I have given to the Levites as their inheritance.' The word <em>terumah</em> (contribution/offering) applied to the tithe elevates it from a tax to a sacred gift — the tithe is given to YHWH (as an offering) and YHWH gives it to the Levites (as inheritance). The entire economic chain runs through YHWH: the Israelites give to YHWH; YHWH gives to those who serve him.</p>",
    "25": "<p>YHWH addresses Moses (not Aaron) about the Levitical obligation — the Levites receive the tithe from Israel, but they must give a tithe of the tithe to YHWH (and it goes to Aaron's family as the most holy portion). The tithe-of-the-tithe principle establishes that receiving a portion from others does not exempt one from giving to YHWH. The Levites are in the middle of the chain, not at its end.</p>",
    "26": "<p><strong>ki et ma'aser beney Yisrael asher yitten laYHWH terumah</strong>: The Levites are to take the tithe they receive from Israel and present a <em>terumah</em> (contribution/heave offering) of it to YHWH. The same language used for Israel's tithe-giving applies to the Levites' giving: the structure mirrors at the Levitical level what happens at the congregational level. Service to God generates its own obligation of return; receiving provision from YHWH does not create exemption from offering back to YHWH.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The Levitical contribution 'shall be credited to you as though it were the grain of the threshing floor and the fullness of the winepress' — the agricultural firstfruits categories. The Levites have no fields or vineyards, but their tithe-of-the-tithe is reckoned as if it were the firstfruits of the land. YHWH treats their monetary contribution as the functional equivalent of the farmer's grain-offering. The principle: the substance of the gift matters, not the category.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The Levitical contribution goes to Aaron the priest — the tithe-of-the-tithe goes up the chain to the chief priest. The Levites receive from Israel, pass the best portion to Aaron, and keep the remainder for their own sustenance. Aaron receives from the Levites as YHWH's representative — the tithe-chain ends at the high priest, just as the offering-chain ends at YHWH's altar.</p>",
    "29": "<p><strong>mikol matnotechem tarimou et kol terumot YHWH mikol chelbo et miqodesho mimennu</strong>: 'From all the gifts you receive, you shall present every contribution owed to YHWH from the best of it, its consecrated portion.' The key qualifier is 'from the best of it' (<em>mikol chelbo</em>) — the obligation is not to give any part but to give the best part. The tithe-of-the-tithe must be the <em>chelev</em> (fat/best portion) of what was received. Half-hearted giving of inferior goods does not satisfy the obligation.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Once the Levites have presented the best portion, the remainder 'shall be counted to the Levites as the produce of the threshing floor and the winepress' — ordinary food, fully available for their households. The act of giving the first-and-best releases the rest for ordinary use. This is the pattern of firstfruits theology throughout Scripture: consecrating the first releases the rest; holding back the first contaminates the whole.</p>",
    "31": "<p><strong>va'achaltem oto bekhol maqom atem uveytechem</strong>: 'You and your households may eat it anywhere, for it is your payment for your service at the tent of meeting.' The Levitical tithe-remainder is portable — it can be eaten 'anywhere,' unlike the most-holy priestly portions that must be eaten in the sanctuary. The Levites' provision supports a mobile, distributed household rather than the fixed priestly household attached to the sanctuary.</p>",
    "32": "<p><strong>velo tis'u alav chet be'harimchem et chelbo mimennu</strong>: 'You will bear no guilt because of it, once you have contributed the best of it.' The chapter closes with a promise and a warning. Promise: contributing the best of the tithe clears the Levites of guilt. Warning: 'do not profane the holy gifts of the Israelites, lest you die.' The system of tithes and priestly portions is not an administrative mechanism but a structure of covenant honor: to handle holy gifts carelessly is a capital offense (the same principle that killed Nadab and Abihu in Lev 10 and Uzzah in 2 Sam 6).</p>"
  }
}

